anslation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘bird’, as for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Vogel  , French   Loiseau  , Czech <b>Ptáček</b> (see   Ptacek  ) and <b>Pták</b>, Polish   Ptak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingbird","meanings":["Native American (Chippewa; also <b>King Bird</b>): translation into English of the Chippewa personal name <i>Ogimaa-bines(i)</i>, meaning literally ‘the bird that is king’ and referring to the mythological bird-like creature thunderbird. See also   Bird   4.","History: The progenitor of the large family of the Kingbirds from the Red Lake, MN, was Ogimaa-bines, a musical gifted Chippewa spiritual leader."]},{"name":"Byrd","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Heaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Malachy, Nuala, Ronan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉanna</b> and <b>Ó hÉinne</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éanna</i>’, a very common personal name of uncertain meaning. It was borne by various early Christian saints, most notably Saint Éanna of Aran. The name has been erroneously understood as containing the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’ and as a result the surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Blackbird","meanings":["Native American (also <b>Black Bird</b>): translation into English of a personal name such as Lakota Sioux <i>Ziŋtkala Sapa</i>, which is composed of <i>ziŋtkala</i> ‘bird’ and <i>sapa</i> ‘black’. See also   Bird   4.","English (Durham): nickname for someone with a dark beard, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>berd</i> ‘beard’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>beard</i>)."]},{"name":"Burd","meanings":["English: variant of   Bird  .","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): nickname for a man with a notable beard, from a southern Yiddish pronunciation of Yiddish <i>bord</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Burt","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Bird  ,   Bright  , or   Burd  .","German: Middle High German <i>burt</i> ‘that 